INTEREST EXPENSE.

THE SLIGHT INCREASE IN 2003 INTEREST EXPENSE WAS PRIMARILY DUE TO A REDUCED BENEFIT FOR CAPITALIZED INTEREST (RELATED TO LOWER CAPITAL SPENDING) AND HIGHER AVERAGE DEBT BALANCES BEING LARGELY OFFSET BY LOWER INTEREST RATES. DECLINING INTEREST RATES ON FLOATING-RATE DEBT DROVE THE REDUCTION IN EXPENSE IN 2002.

INTEREST INCOME.

WHILE AVERAGE CASH BALANCES WERE HIGHER IN 2003, INTEREST INCOME DECREASED DUE TO LOWER INTEREST RATES. THE INCREASE IN 2002 WAS PRIMARILY RELATED TO LARGER AVERAGE CASH BALANCES.

